If $q=-1$, then $6 m^{2}=(6 p)(12 p-1)$, i.e., $m^{2}=p(12 p-1)$. Since $(p, 12 p-1) = 1$, both $p$ and $12 p-1$ must be perfect squares. Let $p=s^{2}$, $12 p-1=t^{2}$, we get $t^{2}-12 s^{2}=-1$. Since $t^{2} \equiv 0$ (mod 3), this case is also impossible.

