$$
\begin{array}{l}
x^{9}-6 x^{7}+9 x^{5}-4 x^{3} \\
=[(x-2)(x-1) x(x+1)] \\
\quad \cdot[(x-1) x(x+1)(x+2)] x,
\end{array}
$$

Since there are two even numbers among four consecutive integers, and one of them is a multiple of 4, their product can be divided by $2^{3}$, so the above expression can be divided by $2^{3} \times 2^{3}=2^{6}$;
$$
\begin{aligned}
\text { Also, } & x^{9}-6 x^{7}+9 x^{5}-4 x^{3} \\
= & {[(x-2)(x-1) x][(x-1) x} \\
& \cdot(x+1)][x(x+1)(x+2)],
\end{aligned}
$$

Since the product of three consecutive integers can be divided by 3, the above expression can be divided by $3^{3}$;
